Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and finely chop @yellow onion{2}. Mince
@garlic{2%cloves}.

Cook aromatics: Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a large #pot{} over
medium high heat. Add onions and @Italian seasoning{1%tbsp}, and toss until
softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add garlic and cook until fragrant, about
~{1%minute}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add @orzo pasta{12%ounce}, @diced tomatoes{2%14oz boxes},
@chicken stock concentrate{2}, and 4 cups water to pot. Bring to a boil, then
reduce to a simmer. Cover and cook until orzo is al dente, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Zest lemon: While orzo simmers, zest and halve @lemon{1}.

When orzo is al dente, stir in @shrimp{20%ounce} and @peas{8%ounce}. Cook until
shrimp are opaque and cooked through and peas are bright green, about
~{5%minutes}.

Stir in @butter{4%tbsp}, and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir in lemon
zest and a squeeze of lemon, to taste. Divide orzo between plates, top with
@parmesan cheese{1/2%cup}, and enjoy!

> One-pot dinners to the rescue! Since everyone seems to love orzo, we thought:
> why not boil it with tomatoes, shrimp, and aromatics to soak up all the
> flavor? Sweet green peas are tossed in at the very end, but we have a
> feeling even the pickiest of eaters won't be complaining about it.